00:43.060 --> 00:52.320
This is Bill Vernon and David Crews. George R.R. Martin is one of a group of new
writers born in the post-war baby boom who is becoming a powerful force in the

00:52.320 --> 01:00.800
field of science fiction. We asked Martin his definition of science fiction.
Science fiction isn't about science. It's what about all literature is about.

01:00.960 --> 01:12.860
It's about people and moral issues and the way people relate to each other and
good and bad and love and death and pain and sorrow and all of that stuff. The

01:12.860 --> 01:21.040
only thing that's different about it is it uses a different set of symbols. It
tries to get us out of our here and now world, just as traditional fantasy has

01:21.040 --> 01:31.280
done for centuries. But instead of using fantasy type symbols, it uses symbols
drawn from what essentially is the new religion of our modern age, science and

01:31.280 --> 01:43.620
technology. The theme that pervades much of Martin's early work is the intrusion
of cold, hard reality into romance. Martin comments on this element. The dreams

01:43.620 --> 01:53.060
that I grew up with, that other writers of my generation grew up with, Howard
Waldrop, John Varley, people like that have spoken about it in their own

01:53.060 --> 02:07.540
writings. And then the reality unfolded. Our dreams came true. But they didn't.
It wasn't the same dreams. It changed. And in most cases, it changed for the

02:07.540 --> 02:19.000
worse. For the worse. There was a story of mine called Patrick Henry, Jupiter
and a Little Red Brick Spaceship that's included in Songs of Stars and Shadows.

02:19.400 --> 02:30.480
Probably not one of my most famous stories or one of my better stories. But it's
one in which this particular question is addressed in a very direct kind of

02:30.480 --> 02:41.540
manner because I use a protagonist who feels the same way. The World Science
Fiction Convention, when Apollo 11 landed on the moon, gave them a special award

02:41.540 --> 02:49.680
for Best Moon Landing Ever, which I think is completely untrue. In science
fiction, there are lots of moon landings that are much more exciting than the

02:49.680 --> 03:02.900
one that Apollo 11 did. In fact, that's the whole point that I support the space
program i dream of uh i think it's a route that mankind should go to and in some

03:02.900 --> 03:09.600
ways it's it's very tragic what's happened to it and what's happened to it is
that nasa really messed it up they took the greatest adventure in human history

03:09.600 --> 03:17.740
and through a supreme superhuman effort and managed to make it boring and that's
what's happened to the american space program and that's what i tried to address

03:17.740 --> 03:30.680
in that particular uh story but the theme in other contexts runs through a lot
of my work, particularly my early work. The fact that we need dreams to sustain

03:30.680 --> 03:40.180
us, and that the dreams are often, I mean that's part of with Morning Comes
Mistfall too, the dreams are better than the reality. Truth and beauty. Beauty

03:40.180 --> 03:49.360
is truth. Truth, beauty that is all you know and all you need to know, but it's
not true. Some things are beautiful but not true. And some things are true but

03:49.360 --> 03:59.780
not beautiful. I grew up in Bayonne, New Jersey. Little industrial city right
outside of New York. At the time, it was one of the major oil refining centers

03:59.780 --> 04:02.800
in the world. It was true, but it wasn't very beautiful.

04:05.520 --> 04:17.780
I read books that took place on Mars and the asteroid belt and planets of other
stars. They were pretty beautiful in their way, but they weren't true.

04:21.140 --> 04:31.780
Things don't work out that conveniently. And that's the whole reality romance
thing that much of my work does concern itself. In an early Martin story, Slide

04:31.780 --> 04:39.620
Show, the space effort is maintained through contributions garnered at
fundraisers. But I wanted to express the fact that I did have reservations and

04:39.620 --> 04:49.860
humanitarian concerns and all that about that Earth. But I still think the
weight of that story is very much towards the space thing, and how pitiful it

04:49.860 --> 04:58.540
has become where they have to go around and give slideshows to rich people and
hope to get a little contributions to continue it. But I do see us going that

04:58.540 --> 05:02.080
way. More on George Martin in our next show.

