06:37.140 --> 06:45.540
This is David Crews and Bill Vernon. Our show today continues the discussion with
science fiction author George Martin. While we were interviewing Martin, he

06:45.540 --> 06:53.420
expressed to us his idea that the American space program is in the doldrums
because of a poor public relations effort by NASA. According to Martin, if NASA

06:53.420 --> 07:02.240
were to play on people's dreams of exploring the unknown rather than to harp on
the mundane tangible benefits, the space program would be much better off. Part

07:02.240 --> 07:11.180
of the reason that we're going that way is the way NASA has sold it. I mean,
it's totally, totally inappropriate. They're trying to make people, they have

07:11.180 --> 07:22.060
people who are poor, they have people who are suffering through social cutbacks,
they have people who don't have enough to eat, whose children are ill-clothed,

07:22.840 --> 07:31.320
who are suffering from poverty and crime and stuff like that. In other words,
who have a hell of a lot of problems in their life. And they're trying to say,

07:31.520 --> 07:40.420
well, we're cutting back social programs, but we don't want to cut back the
space programming, You ought to support this decision because it gave you Teflon

07:40.420 --> 07:52.180
frying pans. Now, if somebody doesn't have any chicken to cook up, the fact that
their frying pan may have Teflon on it is not going to convince them. And the

07:52.180 --> 08:05.560
fact that the space program produced Teflon frying pans is of little interest to
them. Ditto hand calculators. And all of the other benefits the space program is

08:05.560 --> 08:16.180
supposed to have brought us and didn't de-browd us. But these same people have
television sets on which they watch sports. You know, probably were all very

08:16.180 --> 08:18.540
excited about the Super Bowl and the World Series.

08:21.520 --> 08:33.020
Follow Adventure Series and all that. And there's the potential support for the
space program. Not the practical, dull accountant's cell where they show them

08:33.020 --> 08:40.200
the balance sheets and say, well, here's all the Teflon, you know. If you want
to get public support by a space program, you have to get it by making it

08:40.200 --> 08:42.280
exciting, by making it an adventure.

08:45.160 --> 08:55.740
And it is an adventure. It's a colossal adventure. It's enormously exciting. Why
the hell am I addicted to it? Why are all these people here? Why didn't our

08:55.740 --> 09:05.860
entire generation growing up, reading Willy Lay and Werner von Braun and what
was going to happen and the dinosaur projects and the flying wing and the space

09:05.860 --> 09:18.040
stations we were going to have. It was marvelous, heady, wonderful stuff. And
instead they're selling us Teflon. I mean, it's just nonsense. It's the

09:18.040 --> 09:26.960
excitement of it that they should sell us. strange things that might be
discovered, the adventures that are there to be had, the dream of it. That's the

09:26.960 --> 09:36.100
real powering thing. Not that they're going to be able to make better ball
bearings in space because of weightlessness, but the dream of it. That's what

09:36.100 --> 09:36.800
they should push.

09:45.420 --> 09:55.300
Music plays a major role in many of Martin's works from stories such as the
Lonely Songs of Laren Dorr and For a Single Yesterday to the titles of two of his

09:55.300 --> 10:04.820
collections A Song for Lya and The Songs of Stars and Shadows. A popular song,
Brandy, even influenced the plot of the short story Fast Friends. We asked

10:04.820 --> 10:24.260
Martin if he himself as a musician. Well, none whatsoever. No background
whatsoever. I like songs, music, but I really have no aptitude for it. I used to

10:24.260 --> 10:34.060
live with, when I was living in Chicago, I had a number of musician roommates
for a while, and they would bring in other musician friends of theirs who would

10:34.900 --> 10:41.780
invariably because the whole group were musically inclined in one way or another
it would say to me what instrument do you play and I would say I played a

10:41.780 --> 10:48.800
typewriter that's about the closest I've gotten more on George Martin in our
next show

