12:22.340 --> 12:30.960
This is Bill Vernon and David Crews. Science fiction writer George Martin is the
subject of our show today. Martin spent almost a decade writing short stories

12:30.960 --> 12:38.600
before he published his first novel. Here he comments on the importance of the
short story to the beginning writer. I think that's just the way you break into

12:38.600 --> 12:46.200
the field, and that's one of the strengths of science fiction is that it's one
of the few branches of literature that still has a viable short story market

12:46.980 --> 12:57.360
where young writers and beginning writers can learn the ropes, can get their
initial publication. Novels, on the other hand, are not the best way to begin,

12:57.560 --> 13:09.400
as Martin tells us. Novels are large. Novels are formidable pieces of work. You
just don't knock them off in a week or so. And you really have to know what

13:09.400 --> 13:09.880
you're doing.

13:12.740 --> 13:24.500
I wrote a lot of short stories in my early years. Some of them are good, I like
to think. Some of them are maybe even excellent. And some of them are terrible.

13:29.540 --> 13:39.740
And I learned a lot through the process of doing that and also through the
process of selling them. If I had been writing novels, I mean, it's very easy to

13:39.740 --> 13:46.360
wash out writing novels. You spend a year and a half writing a book and then no
one wants to buy it. It's terrible or it falls apart at the end. Part of it's

13:46.360 --> 13:56.160
good, part of it's bad. That's a bad way to begin, I think. I've always felt
that it's much better, especially in a field like science fiction where you can

13:56.160 --> 14:04.820
publish your short stories for any kind of young writer to begin with short
stories, to learn his craft there, also to establish a name for himself by

14:04.820 --> 14:13.240
selling to the markets. It's a much sounder commercial strategy. Martin believes
that if one does not establish himself as a short story writer first, it's more

14:13.240 --> 14:24.020
difficult to break into print. You see in the modern, present commercial
marketplace of literature, you see a whole lot of books coming out, first

14:24.020 --> 14:38.220
novels. There's nothing that's more deadly than a first novel. That did not
always be the case in science fiction. Once upon a time, there was a large

14:38.220 --> 14:44.860
enough audience that bought every science fiction book that came out that a
writer publishing his first novel could be short a certain minimum thing.

14:45.240 --> 14:54.800
Science fiction's gotten too big for that now. That's no longer the case. So a
lot of people, Joe Blow writes his first novel, sells it because it's pretty

14:54.800 --> 15:03.940
good, it gets published, and just dies a dismal, dreary death because no one's
ever heard of him. So unless he has some gimmick, unless there's some reason,

15:03.940 --> 15:12.800
Nobody reads this novel. Nobody gives him a chance. The way I did it in
hindsight is much the better way. I built up a reputation over five or six years

15:12.800 --> 15:22.160
for my short stories, and when I finally did write Dying of the Light, my first
novel, it was not by Joe Blow. It was the first novel by George R. R. Martin,

15:22.540 --> 15:33.500
with trumpets, drumroll, and the world was much more receptive to it than had I
thrown it out beforehand. So I think any writer wanting to break into science

15:33.500 --> 15:44.100
fiction should begin with short stories and should make a reputation with those
and then make the transition to novels. At the end of each story in Martin's

15:44.100 --> 15:53.980
collections is a date and a location. We asked Martin why he ends his stories in
this manner. Instead of writing the end, you put where you were and what time

15:53.980 --> 16:02.620
the story was written. It helps put them in a chronological perspective for
readers who are interested in observing the writer's growth because the order

16:02.620 --> 16:11.160
that they're published in is often not at all an appropriate indication of the
order that they were written in, publishing schedules being what they are. Some

16:11.160 --> 16:18.560
stories are rushed into print, some are held for years. Some stories you can't
sell for years, and you finally find a place for them, and they come out five

16:18.560 --> 16:19.520
years after you wrote them.

16:22.520 --> 16:32.940
So to really get an idea of the kind of evolution changes a writer goes through,
those sorts of dates are important. In our next show, we'll discuss Martin's

16:32.940 --> 16:34.220
novel, Dying of the Light.

