18:10.940 --> 18:19.500
This is David Crews and Bill Vernon. In today's show, we continue our discussion
with science fiction writer George Martin. Martin's first novel was the

18:19.500 --> 18:28.440
enthusiastically received, critically acclaimed Dying of the Light. The story
behind the title of this novel is interesting. I wrote the book as After the

18:28.440 --> 18:45.600
Festival, which was my title for it. I sold the book to Pocket Books at the same
time I sold a version to Analog for serialization in Analog magazine, and they

18:45.600 --> 18:59.800
wanted it cut considerably. So I cut for them by 30,000 words, which is a pretty
substantial cut. And when I did that, I said, well, I want this serial version

18:59.800 --> 19:08.140
published under a different title, because I don't want people reading the
serial and thinking they've read the book. Not one near 30,000 words difference.

19:08.360 --> 19:19.980
The book is a lot better than the serial. So, I told the editor of Analog to
call the serial version Mockman, because my book was going to be called After

19:19.980 --> 19:32.600
the Festival, which I had written it under. He didn't like the title Mach Man,
but he kind of agreed under protest. Then my book publisher calls back and says

19:32.600 --> 19:41.400
that the higher-up, Peter Mayer, who was running the company at the time, big
publishing hotshot, not a science fiction editor, but the head of the whole

19:41.400 --> 19:53.560
Pocket Books empire then, he didn't like After the Festival as a title. because
it wasn't science fictional enough. They were willing to make it after the Star

19:53.560 --> 20:04.740
Festival, but that gave me goose bumps and made me want to decapitate someone,
so I said no-no. But they threw out after the Festival, so I had to come up with

20:04.740 --> 20:15.280
a new title. And I came up with about 12 of them, most of which were pretty
limp, and I sent in the list of these 12, kind of dreading which what they would

20:15.280 --> 20:25.980
pick, because I didn't like any of them. And then, two days after I sent in the
list, I thought of Dying in a Light, and I liked that title a great deal. I

20:25.980 --> 20:36.100
liked it almost as much as after the festival. It's real close. Right now, I
wouldn't know which title I like best. They're both very appropriate for the

20:36.100 --> 20:46.260
book. And the publisher liked Dying in a Light, and I sent it in two days after
the list of 12 bad suggestions. The publisher said, oh, Dying of the Light,

20:46.360 --> 20:55.120
that's fine. We'll call it that. At that point, I called up the editor of Analog
and said, well, I still want a different title, but After the Festival is now

20:55.120 --> 21:06.320
free because the publisher changed it, so call the serial version After the
Festival. So my original title was used on the serial version, and the Dying of

21:06.320 --> 21:15.720
the Light title from Thomas was used on the book, the fuller version. One of the
themes Martin explores in Dying of the Light is that of the misunderstanding

21:15.720 --> 21:29.740
that can develop between people from different cultures. A very significant
point of the whole book is the role of names, which I call it in the book, the

21:29.740 --> 21:39.840
importance of names, really the importance of language and linguistics, to what
we are able to think, to what we are able to conceive. The hero of Dying of the

21:39.840 --> 21:48.340
Light, the protagonist, gets in trouble throughout the book because he insists
on making false translations. He'll see something and he'll say, well, these

21:48.340 --> 21:57.560
people are slaves. But they're not slaves. They're, you know, there's a word for
it in the book, an alien word, and it's different. There are important

21:57.560 --> 22:08.720
differences from slavery, but he sees it only in his own terms. He sees people,
and he has to define them as friends, let us say. When the word is tein, it

22:08.720 --> 22:18.080
means something very different, similar in some ways, different in other ways,
And to really understand another culture, you have to be able to think in their

22:18.080 --> 22:30.960
language, in their terms, and not make false translations to your own terms that
simplify and distort simply by the act of translating. More on George Martin in

22:30.960 --> 22:31.620
our next show.

